\section{Method}
\label{sec:method}

We consider the problem of learning aligned image and text representations from paired data using contrastive pretraining. Given a dataset of image--text pairs, the objective is to learn embedding functions that map images and texts into a shared latent space where matched pairs are close and mismatched pairs are separated. A central challenge in this setting is the construction of informative negative examples that effectively shape the geometry of the embedding space. In what follows, we introduce an optimal-transport-based mechanism for generating structured synthetic negatives that capture aggregate semantic ambiguity across modalities.

\subsection{Notation}
\label{sec:notation}

Let $\{(I_i, T_i)\}_{i=1}^B$ denote a batch of paired images and texts. An image encoder $f_\theta(\cdot)$ maps each image $I_i$ to an embedding $z_i^I \in \mathbb{R}^d$, and a text encoder $g_\phi(\cdot)$ maps each text $T_i$ to an embedding $z_i^T \in \mathbb{R}^d$. All embeddings are $\ell_2$-normalized so that similarity is measured by cosine similarity. We denote by $Z^I = \{z_i^I\}_{i=1}^B$ and $Z^T = \{z_i^T\}_{i=1}^B$ the sets of image and text embeddings within a batch.

Throughout this section, we treat each batch as an empirical distribution over embeddings and operate entirely at the batch level.

\subsection{OT-Based Synthetic Negatives}
\label{sec:ot_negatives}

Contrastive learning frameworks rely critically on the availability of informative negative examples to shape the geometry of the embedding space. In multimodal settings, negatives are typically obtained from random in-batch mismatches or from heuristic hard-negative mining strategies based on pairwise similarity. While effective, such approaches treat negatives as isolated counterexamples and fail to account for the collective structure of semantic confusion that arises when multiple images partially align with a given textual description. Our goal is to move beyond selecting individual negatives and instead characterize and exploit structured regions of ambiguity in the joint embedding space.

We propose to use optimal transport (OT) as a principled mechanism for capturing this aggregate confusion structure and generating synthetic negatives that reflect it. Consider a batch of normalized image and text embeddings forming empirical distributions in a shared latent space. For a given text embedding, several image embeddings may exhibit partial semantic alignment along different dimensions—for example, variations of an object, scene, or attribute. Rather than arbitrarily choosing one such image as a negative, OT models show how semantic mass is distributed across all competing correspondences by computing a soft transport plan between the two modalities.


\paragraph{Cross-Modal Transport Formulation.}
Formally, we define a cross-modal cost matrix $C \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times B}$ based on cosine distance:
\begin{equation}
C_{ij} = 1 - \langle z_i^T, z_j^I \rangle,
\end{equation}
where $\langle \cdot, \cdot \rangle$ denotes cosine similarity. To prevent trivial alignment, diagonal entries corresponding to matched image--text pairs are masked, ensuring that transport mass is assigned only to mismatched pairs.

We compute an entropy-regularized optimal transport plan $\Pi \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times B}$ by solving
\begin{equation}
\Pi = \arg\min_{\Pi \in \mathcal{U}} \sum_{i,j} \Pi_{ij} C_{ij}
      + \varepsilon \sum_{i,j} \Pi_{ij} \log \Pi_{ij},
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{U}$ denotes the set of couplings with uniform row and column marginals. The resulting transport plan encodes the degree of semantic competition between each text embedding and all image embeddings in the batch.

\paragraph{Barycentric Synthesis of Synthetic Negatives.}
Given the transport plan $\Pi$, we construct a synthetic negative image embedding for each text via barycentric projection:
\begin{equation}
\tilde{z}_i^I = \sum_{j=1}^B \frac{\Pi_{ij}}{\sum_{k} \Pi_{ik}} \, z_j^I.
\end{equation}
This convex combination aggregates competing image embeddings according to their transport mass, producing a geometry-aware synthetic negative that represents a direction of semantic confusion rather than a single instance. Gradients are stopped through $\Pi$ so that the transport plan acts as a geometry-derived augmentation operator rather than a learnable transformation.

This construction naturally adapts to the semantic density of the batch. When a text embedding has multiple plausible image correspondences, the transport mass is diffuse, and the barycentric projection aggregates their shared structure. Conversely, when such competition is absent and a single image dominates, the transport mass concentrates and the synthetic negative collapses toward that image. In this way, the method gracefully interpolates between aggregation and selection depending on the underlying embedding geometry.

\paragraph{Local Restriction and Limiting Cases.}
The barycentric construction above relies on an implicit but important geometric assumption: that convex combinations of embeddings preserve semantic meaning. This assumption is valid only when embeddings lie within a \emph{local semantic neighborhood}. Averaging representations corresponding to unrelated concepts—for example, mixing embeddings of ``dog'' and ``airplane''—produces points that do not correspond to any coherent visual concept and therefore cannot serve as meaningful negatives.

For this reason, locality is not merely an optimization but a necessary condition for semantic validity. To respect this constraint, we restrict the support of the transport problem to a local neighborhood around each text embedding. Specifically, for each text embedding, we identify the top-$m$ most similar image embeddings under cosine similarity and solve the optimal transport problem only over this subset. This restriction ensures that barycentric synthesis combines only semantically related images, preserving the local linearity assumption required for meaningful interpolation.

In addition to improving semantic coherence, this local restriction reduces computational complexity from $\mathcal{O}(B^2)$ to $\mathcal{O}(B m)$, enabling efficient use of OT-based synthesis in practical training regimes.

The proposed formulation naturally subsumes hard negative selection as a special case. When the transport mass concentrates on a single dominant correspondence, the barycentric projection reduces to selecting a single hard negative guided by the transport plan. We refer to this degenerate case as \emph{OT-Select}. Our full method, \emph{OT-Mix}, strictly generalizes this behavior by synthesizing negatives that reflect aggregate semantic competition rather than isolated alternatives.

This distinction is critical: while hard negative selection captures individual confusions, OT-Mix captures the structure of ambiguity when multiple images compete semantically for a given text. Our ablation studies demonstrate that this aggregation yields consistently stronger supervision than selection alone.

\paragraph{Why Optimal Transport Instead of Top-$k$ Selection?}
A natural alternative to our approach is to select hard negatives by ranking in-batch image embeddings according to cosine similarity and choosing the top-$k$ most similar mismatches. While effective, such selection-based strategies operate independently for each query and treat negatives as isolated counterexamples. In contrast, optimal transport characterizes semantic confusion at the level of the \emph{entire batch} by solving a global coupling problem with marginal constraints.

This distinction is particularly important for synthetic negative generation. When multiple image embeddings are comparably similar to a given text, top-$k$ selection must arbitrarily choose among them, producing brittle and potentially redundant supervision. Optimal transport instead assigns continuous mass across all competing correspondences, encoding their relative semantic influence. The resulting transport weights provide a principled mechanism for aggregating these competitors via barycentric projection, yielding synthetic negatives that reflect shared directions of ambiguity rather than individual instances.

From this perspective, hard negative mining and OT-based synthesis are not competing ideas but nested ones. When transport mass concentrates on a single correspondence, barycentric synthesis reduces to selecting a single hard negative (OT-Select). When semantic competition is distributed, OT-Mix strictly generalizes selection by interpolating across competitors in a globally consistent manner. Our ablation studies empirically validate that this soft aggregation yields more informative negatives than both cosine top-$k$ selection and OT-Select.

\paragraph{Training Dynamics and Scheduling.}
The effectiveness of OT-generated negatives depends critically on the quality of the underlying embedding geometry. Early in training, representations are poorly organized, and transport plans primarily reflect noise rather than semantic structure. Introducing OT-based synthesis at this stage can inject instability rather than useful supervision. We therefore delay the introduction of OT-generated negatives until the embedding space has begun to organize under a standard contrastive objective.

Moreover, because the embedding geometry evolves gradually during training, recomputing transport plans at every iteration is unnecessary and computationally expensive. Instead, we update the transport plan periodically every $k$ steps and reuse it for subsequent batches, ensuring smooth evolution of the OT signal while significantly reducing overhead. In the following section, we describe how these OT-generated negatives are integrated into the contrastive learning objective.

\subsection{Contrastive Learning Objective}
\label{sec:loss}

We now describe how OT-generated synthetic negatives are integrated into the contrastive learning objective. Our loss formulation builds upon recent advances in contrastive representation learning for vision--language models, while incorporating additional supervision signals derived from optimal transport.

\paragraph{Baseline Contrastive Objective.}
Given a batch of paired image and text embeddings $\{(z_i^I, z_i^T)\}_{i=1}^B$, the standard contrastive learning objective encourages matched pairs to have high similarity while discouraging mismatched pairs. Rather than using a softmax-based InfoNCE loss, we adopt the sigmoid-based contrastive objective introduced in SigLIP, which has been shown to provide improved stability and performance in regimes with limited batch sizes.

For each image--text pair $(i,j)$, we define the similarity score
\begin{equation}
s_{ij} = \langle z_i^I, z_j^T \rangle,
\end{equation}
where all embeddings are $\ell_2$-normalized. The baseline contrastive loss is then given by
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\text{base}} =
\frac{1}{B^2}
\sum_{i=1}^B \sum_{j=1}^B
\log\left(1 + \exp\left(\ell_{ij} \cdot s_{ij}\right)\right),
\end{equation}
where $\ell_{ij} = -1$ if $i=j$ (positive pair) and $\ell_{ij} = +1$ otherwise (negative pair). This formulation treats contrastive learning as a collection of independent binary classification problems, avoiding the strong coupling between samples imposed by softmax normalization and enabling robust optimization with moderate batch sizes.

\paragraph{OT-Based Binary Negative Loss.}
While the baseline objective enforces global separation between matched and mismatched pairs, it treats all negatives equally and does not explicitly account for structured semantic ambiguity. To address this, we introduce an auxiliary binary loss term that incorporates OT-generated synthetic negatives.

For each text embedding $z_i^T$, we construct a synthetic negative image embedding $\tilde{z}_i^I$ via barycentric projection as described in Section~\ref{sec:ot_negatives}. We then define an OT-based binary negative loss
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\text{OT}} =
\frac{1}{B}
\sum_{i=1}^B
\log\left(1 + \exp\left(\langle z_i^T, \tilde{z}_i^I \rangle\right)\right),
\end{equation}
which penalizes high similarity between each text embedding and its corresponding synthetic negative. This loss term explicitly encourages the model to separate each anchor from a direction of aggregate semantic confusion rather than from isolated negative instances.

Importantly, this formulation mirrors the structure of the baseline sigmoid contrastive loss and can be interpreted as introducing an additional targeted negative comparison for each sample. Because the synthetic negative aggregates multiple competing alternatives, this penalty provides a more informative and geometry-aware training signal than standard in-batch negatives alone.

\paragraph{Combined Objective and Training Schedule.}
The final training objective combines the baseline contrastive loss with the OT-based negative loss:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L} = \mathcal{L}_{\text{base}} + \alpha \, \mathcal{L}_{\text{OT}},
\end{equation}
where $\alpha$ controls the relative strength of the OT-based supervision. To ensure stable optimization, we employ a warm-up strategy in which $\alpha$ is initially set to zero and gradually increased after the embedding space has begun to organize under the baseline contrastive objective. This prevents noisy or degenerate transport plans from destabilizing early training and allows OT-generated negatives to be introduced only once they reflect meaningful semantic structure.

Together, these loss components enable the model to learn a globally aligned embedding space while simultaneously refining local decision boundaries using structured, transport-derived synthetic negatives.


\subsection{Training Dynamics and Schedule}
\label{sec:schedule}

The effectiveness of OT-generated synthetic negatives depends critically on the quality and stability of the underlying embedding geometry. Unlike standard in-batch negatives, which are immediately available from random mismatches, OT-based negatives rely on meaningful cross-modal structure in the embedding space. Early in training, representations are poorly organized and similarity scores largely reflect noise rather than semantic relationships. Transport plans computed at this stage are therefore unreliable and can inject spurious supervision if used directly.

\paragraph{Warm-Up Phase.}
To address this issue, we adopt a staged training procedure. During an initial warm-up phase, the model is trained exclusively using the baseline contrastive objective described in Section~\ref{sec:loss}, without OT-based supervision. This allows the embedding space to develop coarse semantic organization, ensuring that similarity scores and transport plans computed later reflect meaningful structure rather than random initialization effects. Empirically, introducing OT-based negatives too early leads to unstable optimization and degraded performance.

\paragraph{Gradual Introduction of OT-Based Supervision.}
After the warm-up phase, OT-generated synthetic negatives are introduced gradually by increasing the weighting coefficient $\alpha$ in the combined objective. Rather than activating OT supervision abruptly, we employ a smooth ramp-up schedule for $\alpha$, allowing the model to adapt progressively to the additional training signal. This strategy stabilizes optimization by preventing sudden shifts in the loss landscape and ensures that OT-based supervision refines, rather than overrides, the representation learned under the baseline objective.

\paragraph{Periodic OT Updates.}
Computing optimal transport plans incurs nontrivial computational overhead and reflects the current geometry of the embedding space. Since this geometry evolves gradually during training, recomputing the transport plan at every iteration is unnecessary. Instead, we update the transport plan periodically every $k$ optimization steps and reuse it for subsequent batches. This periodic update scheme serves two complementary purposes: it significantly reduces computational cost, and it enforces temporal smoothness in the OT signal, preventing rapid fluctuations in synthetic negatives that could destabilize training. In Section~\ref{sec:experiments}, we analyze the sensitivity of model performance to the OT update frequency $k$.

\subsection{Architectural Details}
\label{sec:architecture}

Our framework follows a dual-encoder architecture commonly used in vision--language contrastive learning, consisting of separate image and text encoders that map inputs into a shared embedding space. This design enables scalable training and allows similarity computation to be expressed directly in terms of dot products between normalized embeddings.

\paragraph{Image Encoder.}
Images are processed by a convolutional vision backbone $f_\theta(\cdot)$, which maps each input image $I_i$ to a feature vector in $\mathbb{R}^{d_v}$. In our experiments, we adopt a ResNet-based architecture as the image encoder, following prior work in contrastive representation learning. The output feature vector is passed through a projection head to obtain the final image embedding $z_i^I \in \mathbb{R}^d$ used for contrastive learning.

\paragraph{Text Encoder.}
Text inputs are processed by a transformer-based text encoder $g_\phi(\cdot)$, which maps each text sequence $T_i$ to a pooled representation in $\mathbb{R}^{d_t}$. We use the encoder’s pooled output as the text feature representation, which is then passed through a projection head to produce the final text embedding $z_i^T \in \mathbb{R}^d$. Using a pooled representation ensures that each text is represented by a single vector, enabling optimal transport to be computed across collections of text embeddings at the batch level.

\paragraph{Projection Heads and Normalization.}
Both image and text features are mapped into the shared embedding space using lightweight projection heads. Following prior findings in contrastive learning, we employ linear projection layers that map encoder outputs to the common embedding dimension $d$. The projected embeddings are $\ell_2$-normalized before similarity computation, ensuring that cosine similarity corresponds to a dot product on the unit hypersphere. This normalization is essential for stable contrastive training and for defining meaningful transport costs based on angular distance.

\paragraph{Design Considerations for OT Integration.}
Several architectural choices are made specifically to support OT-based synthetic negative generation. First, we ensure that both modalities produce embeddings of identical dimensionality, allowing barycentric projections to be computed directly in the shared space. Second, projection heads are kept linear to preserve local linear structure in the embedding space, which underlies the semantic validity of barycentric mixing. Finally we stop gradients through the transport plan $\Pi$ (and the resulting synthetic negatives $\tilde{z}_i^I$), treating OT as a geometry-derived augmentation operator rather than a learnable module. This design is critical. If gradients were allowed to flow through $\Pi$, the encoders could implicitly manipulate the transport solution to reduce the difficulty of the generated negatives---for example, by shaping the similarity geometry so that transport mass concentrates on already-dissimilar images or becomes overly diffuse. In this regime, the OT objective can be satisfied by \emph{changing the negatives} rather than improving the representation. Moreover, differentiating through entropic OT introduces a tightly coupled feedback loop between representation learning and plan estimation, which can amplify small geometric perturbations into large changes in the transport plan and destabilize training. By detaching $\Pi$, we ensure that synthetic negatives remain fixed targets determined by the current embedding geometry, mirroring the stabilization role of momentum targets in MoCo and stop-gradient mechanisms in self-distillation methods.

These architectural choices strike a balance between expressive capacity and geometric regularity, ensuring that the learned embedding space is well suited for both contrastive alignment and OT-based synthetic negative generation.

\subsection{Implementation Details}
\label{sec:implementation}

We describe the practical implementation choices used in our experiments, including datasets, data preprocessing, training configuration, and optimal transport computation. Unless otherwise specified, all models are trained end-to-end using standard stochastic gradient optimization.

\paragraph{Datasets.}
We evaluate our approach on image--text datasets commonly used in vision--language representation learning. In our primary experiments, we use the Flickr8K dataset, which contains approximately 8,000 images, each paired with multiple textual captions. This dataset provides a controlled setting for studying the behavior of structured negative sampling under limited data and batch size regimes. Additional datasets and scaling behavior are discussed in Section~\ref{sec:experiments}.

For datasets with multiple captions per image, each image--caption pair is treated as an independent training example, following standard practice in contrastive learning. During batching, captions corresponding to the same image may appear multiple times, but each instance is considered a distinct positive pair.

\paragraph{Image Preprocessing and Augmentation.}
Images are resized and cropped to a fixed spatial resolution of $224 \times 224$ before being passed to the image encoder. During training, we apply a set of standard data augmentations commonly used in contrastive representation learning, including random resized cropping, random horizontal flipping, and moderate color jitter. These augmentations are applied prior to encoding and serve to encourage invariance to low-level appearance variations. At evaluation time, we use deterministic resizing and center cropping.

\paragraph{Text Processing.}
Text inputs are tokenized using a fixed vocabulary tokenizer associated with the chosen text encoder. Input sequences are padded or truncated to a fixed maximum length to enable efficient batching. The pooled output of the text encoder is used as the text representation, yielding a single embedding vector per caption. This pooled representation ensures compatibility with batch-level optimal transport computation.

\paragraph{Training Configuration.}
All models are trained using the AdamW optimizer with standard momentum parameters. Learning rates are selected based on the baseline contrastive objective and held fixed across experiments to ensure fair comparison. We use a fixed batch size throughout training to avoid confounding effects between batch size and negative sampling strategy. The weighting coefficient $\alpha$ for the OT-based loss is initialized to zero and increased according to a linear ramp-up schedule following the warm-up phase described in Section~\ref{sec:schedule}.

\paragraph{Optimal Transport Computation.}
Optimal transport plans are computed on mini-batch embeddings using an entropy-regularized formulation. We employ a Sinkhorn-style iterative solver to obtain approximate transport plans efficiently. Diagonal entries corresponding to matched image--text pairs are masked prior to transport computation. To reduce computational overhead and improve stability, transport plans are recomputed every $k$ training steps and reused for subsequent batches. In all experiments, optimal transport is computed over local semantic neighborhoods defined by the top-$m$ most similar image embeddings per text. We vary $m$ in ablation studies to examine the effect of neighborhood size on performance and computational cost.

\paragraph{Evaluation Protocol.}
We evaluate learned representations using standard image--text retrieval metrics. Given a trained model, image-to-text and text-to-image retrieval are performed by ranking candidates according to cosine similarity in the shared embedding space. We report recall at $K$ (R@1, R@5, R@10) for both retrieval directions. All reported results are averaged over multiple runs with different random seeds.

Additional implementation details, including hyperparameter settings and ablation configurations, are provided in the supplementary material.

\section{Experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}

\subsection{Experimental Setup}
\label{sec:setup}

We evaluate the proposed OT-based synthetic negative framework on image--text retrieval tasks, following standard protocols in multimodal contrastive learning. Our goal is to assess whether OT-generated negatives improve representation quality beyond existing contrastive baselines under controlled training conditions.

\paragraph{Datasets.}
We conduct our primary experiments on the Flickr8K dataset, which contains approximately 8,000 images, each annotated with five natural language captions. Flickr8K provides a compact yet semantically rich benchmark that is well suited for studying hard negative generation under limited batch size and data regimes. Following common practice, we treat each image--caption pair as an independent positive example during training.

\paragraph{Evaluation Protocol.}
We evaluate learned representations using bidirectional image--text retrieval. Given a trained model, image-to-text and text-to-image retrieval are performed by ranking candidates according to cosine similarity in the shared embedding space. Performance is measured using Recall@K (R@1, R@5, R@10), which reports the percentage of queries for which the correct match appears among the top $K$ retrieved results. All metrics are reported for both retrieval directions.

\paragraph{Baselines.}
We compare our method against strong contrastive learning baselines trained under identical architectural and optimization settings. Specifically, we consider:
(i) a standard CLIP-style contrastive objective using in-batch negatives,
(ii) a Sigmoid-based contrastive loss (SigLIP-style) designed for smaller batch regimes, and
(iii) a hard negative mining baseline that selects top-$k$ most similar in-batch negatives based on cosine similarity.
These baselines allow us to isolate the effect of OT-based negative generation from other factors such as batch size or loss formulation.

\paragraph{Training Protocol.}
All models are trained end-to-end using the same image and text encoders, projection heads, optimizer settings, and batch sizes. We employ a two-stage training schedule consisting of an initial warm-up phase using only the baseline contrastive objective, followed by a second phase in which OT-based synthetic negatives are gradually introduced. The relative weighting of the OT-based loss term is controlled by a ramp-up coefficient, as described in Section~\ref{sec:schedule}. Unless otherwise stated, batch size and learning rate are held fixed across all experiments.

\paragraph{Optimal Transport Configuration.}
For experiments involving OT-based negatives, transport plans are computed on mini-batch embeddings using an entropy-regularized formulation. To reduce computational overhead and improve stability, OT plans are recomputed every $k$ training steps and reused across subsequent batches. In addition to full batch transport, we evaluate a local OT variant that restricts transport to the top-$m$ most similar image embeddings for each text query. The impact of these design choices is examined in the ablation studies.

\paragraph{Implementation Details.}
All experiments are implemented in PyTorch and trained on a single GPU. To ensure reproducibility, results are averaged over multiple runs with different random seeds. Additional implementation details and hyperparameter settings are provided in the supplementary material.

